\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Marginal Valuation to Recover 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Dear Lars, thanks to the robustness concerns approach I think that I can
 produce an inverse mapping between jump intensities and the primitives
 of switching costs 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \kappa,F\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 This is of interest because it makes the estimation algorithm for the primitive
s much simpler.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that Aleksei solves this inverse mapping problem using the marginal
 valuation in an environment with constant drift and volatility and scalar
 continuation values after jumps (state-independent continuation values).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
My framework is considerably harder, it has drift and volatility control
 and the jump continuation value 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{\ell}\left(w\right)$
\end_inset

 is state-dependent.

\color red
 An inverse mapping cannot be found with CRRA utility.
 However, with a particular case of a robustness concerns problem an inverse
 mapping can be found.

\color inherit
 The insight is that in this case, the relevant jump value is the jump of
 logarithms and this simplifies tractable marginal valuations a lot! The
 following short note shows this carefully.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I think this might be a potentially nice contribution too.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Value function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $y\left(w\right)$
\end_inset

 denote the value of adjusting given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
y\left(w\right)\equiv & \,\hat{v}\left(w^{*}\right)-\hat{v}\left(w\right)+\log\left(w-f+\epsilon\right)-\log\left(w^{*}+\epsilon\right)
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f,\epsilon$
\end_inset

 are parameters and 
\begin_inset Formula $w^{*}$
\end_inset

 is the optimal reinjection point satifying 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
w^{*}= & \,\text{argmax}_{w}\left[\hat{v}\left(w\right)-\log\left(w+\epsilon\right)\right].
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{w},\sigma_{w}$
\end_inset

 be the drift of the wealth to durable ratio
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
\mu_{w}\left(w,c,\theta\right)= & \,\left[rw+r^{e}\theta w-c-\left(1-\epsilon\right)\left(r+s\right)\right],\qquad\sigma_{w}\left(w,\theta\right)=\sigma w\theta
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{e}$
\end_inset

 is the risk premium, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is the risky portfolio share, 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is non-durable consumption and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1-\epsilon\right)\left(r+s\right)$
\end_inset

 is the mortgage payment term.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then the value function satisfies the HJB equation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
\delta\hat{v}\left(w\right)= & \,\alpha\log c^{*}+\left(\mu_{w}\left(w,c^{*},\theta^{*}\right)+\sigma_{w}\left(w,\theta^{*}\right)h^{*}\right)\hat{v}^{\prime}\left(w\right)+\frac{\left[\sigma_{w}\left(w,\theta^{*}\right)\right]^{2}}{2}\hat{v}^{\prime\prime}\left(w\right)+\frac{1}{2}\frac{1}{\gamma-1}\left(h^{*}\right)^{2}\\
 & \,+\mathcal{J}^{*}\left(w\right)E_{\psi}\left[g^{*}\left(\psi\right)\left\{ y\left(w\right)-\psi\right\} +\frac{1}{\gamma-1}\left(1-g^{*}\left(\psi\right)+g^{*}\left(\psi\right)\log g^{*}\left(\psi\right)\right)|\psi<y\left(w\right)\right]
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{*},\theta^{*},h^{*},g^{*},\mathcal{J}^{*}$
\end_inset

 are policy functions and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{J}\left(w\right)=\kappa F\left(y\left(w\right)\right)$
\end_inset

.
 FOC are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
c: & \qquad\frac{\alpha}{c^{*}}-\hat{v}^{\prime}\left(w\right)=0\\
h: & \qquad h^{*}=\left(1-\gamma\right)\sigma\theta wv^{\prime}\\
g: & \qquad g^{*}\left(\psi\right)=\,\exp\left[\left(1-\gamma\right)\left(y-\psi\right)\right]\\
\theta: & \qquad\left(r^{e}w+\sigma wh^{*}\right)\hat{v}^{\prime}\left(w\right)+\left(\sigma w\right)^{2}\theta^{*}\hat{v}^{\prime\prime}\left(w\right)=0
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset

multiply the FOC for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{*}/w$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
\left(r^{e}\theta+\sigma h^{*}\theta\right)\hat{v}^{\prime}\left(w\right)+\left(\sigma\theta^{*}\right)^{2}w\hat{v}^{\prime\prime}\left(w\right)= & \,0,\label{eq:FOCtheta}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset

this computation will become handy when computing marginal valuations because
 it is related to the derivative with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Marginal Valuation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Take the derivative with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
\delta\hat{v}^{\prime}\left(w\right)= & \,\left(\mu_{w}\left(w,c^{*},\theta^{*}\right)+\sigma_{w}\left(w,\theta^{*}\right)h^{*}\right)\hat{v}^{\prime\prime}\left(w\right)+\frac{\left[\sigma_{w}\left(w,\theta^{*}\right)\right]^{2}}{2}\hat{v}^{\prime\prime\prime}\left(w\right)\\
 & \,+\left(r+r^{e}\theta+\sigma\theta^{*}h^{*}\right)\hat{v}^{\prime}\left(w\right)+w\left(\theta^{*}\sigma\right)^{2}\hat{v}^{\prime\prime}\left(w\right)\\
 & \,+\mathcal{J}^{*}\left(w\right)E_{\psi}\left[g^{*}\left(\psi\right)\left(-\hat{v}^{\prime}\left(w\right)+\frac{1}{w-f+\epsilon}\right)|\psi<y\left(w\right)\right]
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset

where the derivatives with respect to policies 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{*},\theta^{*},h^{*},g^{*},\mathcal{J}^{*}$
\end_inset

 do not appear because of the Envelope Theorem.
 Using equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FOCtheta"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 we can simplify the second line of the marginal value function and obtain
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
\delta\hat{v}^{\prime}\left(w\right)= & \,\left(\mu_{w}\left(w,c^{*},\theta^{*}\right)+\sigma_{w}\left(w,\theta^{*}\right)h^{*}\right)\hat{v}^{\prime\prime}\left(w\right)+\frac{\left[\sigma_{w}\left(w,\theta^{*}\right)\right]^{2}}{2}\hat{v}^{\prime\prime\prime}\left(w\right)\\
 & \,+r\hat{v}^{\prime}\left(w\right)\\
 & \,+\mathcal{J}^{*}\left(w\right)E_{\psi}\left[g^{*}\left(\psi\right)\left(-\hat{v}^{\prime}\left(w\right)+\frac{1}{w-f+\epsilon}\right)|\psi<y\left(w\right)\right]
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset

Finally, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{v}^{\prime}\equiv u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{g}\left(y\left(w\right)\right)\equiv E_{\psi}\left[g^{*}\left(\psi\right)|\psi<y\left(w\right)\right]$
\end_inset

 then rearranging and following Hansen and Souganidis (2025), we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
\left(\delta-r+\mathcal{J}^{*}\left(w\right)\overline{g}\left(y\left(w\right)\right)\right)u\left(w\right)= & \,\mathcal{J}^{*}\left(w\right)\overline{g}\left(y\left(w\right)\right)\frac{1}{w-f+\epsilon}\\
 & \,+\left(\mu_{w}\left(w,c^{*},\theta^{*}\right)+\sigma_{w}\left(w,\theta^{*}\right)h^{*}\right)u^{\prime}\left(w\right)+\frac{\left[\sigma_{w}\left(w,\theta^{*}\right)\right]^{2}}{2}u^{\prime\prime}\left(w\right).
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to note that there is no contribution from jump sensitivities
 because in my model jump intensities are optimally chosen, so their derivatives
 disappear because of the Envelope Theorem.
 This is an insight of problems with the so called Impulse Hamiltonian (Alvarez,
 Lippi and Souganidis (2023)).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Quasi-Inverse Mapping.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I call the following a quasi-inverse mapping because the mapping between
 jump intensities and primitives for costs 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa,F$
\end_inset

 depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{J}^{*}\left(w\right)$
\end_inset

 and a given jump distortion function 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{g}$
\end_inset

.
 However, this is useful since it will illustrate the procedure for the
 actual inverse mapping below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given two functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{J}^{*}\left(w\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{g}\left(y\left(w\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 we can compute the marginal values 
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(w\right)$
\end_inset

 through finite differences because a guess for 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is all what is needed to compute optimal policies 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{*},\theta^{*},h^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 With the marginal value 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 one can recover 
\begin_inset Formula $w^{*}=\,\text{argmax}_{w}\left[\hat{v}\left(w\right)-\log\left(w+\epsilon\right)\right]$
\end_inset

 using a marginal condition 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
u\left(w^{*}\right)-\frac{1}{w^{*}+\epsilon}= & \,0.
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset

With 
\begin_inset Formula $w^{*}$
\end_inset

 at hand one can compute 
\begin_inset Formula $y\left(w\right)$
\end_inset

 the value of adjusting
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
y\left(w\right)\equiv & \,\hat{v}\left(w^{*}\right)-\hat{v}\left(w\right)+\log\left(w-f+\epsilon\right)-\log\left(w^{*}+\epsilon\right)=\int_{w}^{w^{*}}u\left(w\right)dw+\log\left(w-f+\epsilon\right)-\log\left(w^{*}+\epsilon\right)
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset

and invert the jump intensity
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
\mathcal{J}^{*}\left(w\right)= & \,\kappa F\left(y\left(w\right)\right)
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset

to recover 
\begin_inset Formula $F,\kappa$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Actual Inverse Mapping.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The procedure above does not create an inverse mapping because of the need
 to guess two functions at the same time 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{J}^{*}\left(w\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{g}\left(y\left(w\right)\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In order to create an actual inverse mapping between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{J}^{*}\left(w\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa,F$
\end_inset

, I can choose to solve a 
\series bold
different problem 
\series default
in which 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{*}\left(\psi\right)$
\end_inset

 distortions are misspeficication concerns over the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 of costs 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 and not over the jump intensity 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{J}^{*}\left(w\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Namely, choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{g}=E_{\psi}\left[g^{*}\left(\psi\right)|\psi<y\left(w\right)\right]=1$
\end_inset

.
 In this case the marginal valuation equation is simply
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
\left(\delta-r+\mathcal{J}^{*}\left(w\right)\right)u\left(w\right)= & \,\mathcal{J}^{*}\left(w\right)\frac{1}{w-f+\epsilon}\\
 & \,+\left(\mu_{w}\left(w,c^{*},\theta^{*}\right)+\sigma_{w}\left(w,\theta^{*}\right)h^{*}\right)u^{\prime}\left(w\right)+\frac{\left[\sigma_{w}\left(w,\theta^{*}\right)\right]^{2}}{2}u^{\prime\prime}\left(w\right)
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset

and it can be solved without any input from 
\begin_inset Formula $F,\kappa$
\end_inset

 given 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{J}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Operationalize mapping.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
c: & \qquad\frac{\alpha}{c^{*}}-u\left(w\right)=0\\
h: & \qquad h^{*}=\left(1-\gamma\right)\theta^{*}\sigma wu\left(w\right)\\
\theta: & \qquad\left(r^{e}w+\sigma wh^{*}\right)u\left(w\right)+\left(\sigma w\right)^{2}\theta^{*}u^{\prime}\left(w\right)=0
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset

subsituting distortion's solution into portfolio solution 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
\theta^{*}\sigma w= & \,\frac{r^{e}u\left(w\right)}{\sigma\left[\left(\gamma-1\right)u\left(w\right)^{2}-u^{\prime}\left(w\right)\right]}
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_body
